<|startoftext|>I've been here a couple times on the last few birthdays and today was my first time with the waitstaff.  The food was not bad.  The fried chicken is something I love even though many places have a chicken sub combo and I loved it.  It was not too spicy either.  The biscuits were not very fluffy either.   It was not really filling at all, I'm sorry that they didn't have more stuff.   \n\nOur servers were pretty good.  I love that even when we were sitting close to one another.  I wish they had more booths.  For birthdays and other special occasions I expect that.  I wish there was something like that here.  \n\nMy favorite thing was the tea.  It's amazing.  So delicious.  There was a special place with a specialty drink I think called a iced coffee.  It was a lot of fun watching them dance this morning and they were having such a great time I don't see why you don't come here again.<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>So, I have always tried to support local independent businesses, even to the point of travel from state to state.  I have always been a small business owner.\n\nI support small businesses.  I am passionate about supporting small businesses.\n\nBusiness itself is small, but it does support small businesses.  The people who run it have never been happy that we have a local business, and it supports local businesses.  \n\nI would give them 5 stars simply because I support small businesses, and I support supporting small business.  It supports local people.  \n\nThere was a time when I supported a large chain.  It supported me when local businesses were bad.  I would stand in line to support local businesses, and I would get upset when chains went out of business.  I can no longer do that.  Local businesses want local people, and small businesses should support local people as well.  \n\nThe other side of the coin is that small businesses support the local community, but it has unfortunately become much of a suburban-like place.  They have low quality choices and the local area is so isolated.  It used to be a great area, but it's taking a turn for the worse.  No local stores, no local food options, no local bar.... which leaves a lot to be desired.<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>I visited this place with my family one afternoon a year ago. We were celebrating my granddaughter's birthday and we decided to have a birthday dinner. We placed our orders and when it came time, our food was cold by the time we got there. My granddaughter was very excited because they had sausage and potatoes and I'm glad they didn't, because it was really dry. What they did have was the sausage and potatoes which was fine. We also ordered the homemade chips which I was surprised we didn't get a can of chips and a bag of chips. We also ordered a dessert, and it was the homemade cookie that came with the dinner. The cookies were great and I don't think I bought a cake because I thought it looked too sweet and decadent but the cookie was amazing! It was a great experience and I don't think I would have paid $40 for a cookie, or even a can of chips. The restaurant was clean and the food was served in a timely manner. I will definitely be returning to this place.<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>Huge and cozy space in the heart of the Quartier des spectacles Notre Dame.  The wine list was impressive and reasonably priced.  The service was warm and friendly,  and our server, Chris, offered recommendations and informed us of new openings in the city.  \n\nThe restaurant itself is set in an old port, and although they offer some items a step above at Unblanc, they do share the space with a small boutique.  \n\nDinner, wine and spirits were all on point with this charming establishment.  Thanks for Sharing the City!<
